[2] Japan: meeting
Date: Thu 12 Jan 2006 18:58:41 -0000
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Sidney Morning Herald, 13 Jan 2006 [edited]
<http://smh.com.au/news/world/bird-flu-vaccines-too-far-from-frontline-says-un/2006/01/12/1136956303599.html>


Anti-bird-flu drugs should be stockpiled at the disease's frontline
in Asia, ready to be shipped to threatened populations in the
critical 1st 2 weeks of an outbreak, the World Health Organisation
said yesterday. Asia was "still the epicentre of the threat to global
health posed by this virus", said the regional director of WHO,
Shigeru Omi [at a 2-day meeting of Asian countries and international
organisations on bird flu in Tokyo.]

Stockpiles are only now being built up but are in Europe and the US,
too far away for comfort. One or 2 stockpiles should be located in
Asia, where they could be drawn on in an emergency, Dr Omi told
representatives of 27 countries, including Australia, at a meeting in Tokyo.

All countries need a rapid reaction plan or the only feasible
approach to the disease -- containment -- would fail, according to a
senior WHO official, who said a global influenza taskforce would be
set up within weeks. But the logistics of managing an outbreak in
Asia remain complex. Laos, one of the poorest countries in the
region, told the conference it had neither the pathology laboratories
to quickly confirm an outbreak nor the trucks to deliver medicine.

[Byline: Deborah Cameron]

